the \u2018bachelors\u2019 of Warwick's household during times of peace, and was required to attend the earl at tournaments and in the event of war.\n\nWarwick granted Herle the wardenship of [[Barnard Castle]] along with its forests and lands, this, it has been stated made Herle a pivotal figure in the running of the earl's estates. Herle's was further granted a lifetime lease on several lands and rents in the vicinity of the Castle.\n\n\"''In September 1343, Herle obtained a pardon of the king's suit for homicides, felonies, robberies and larcenies perpetrated by him and any consequent outlawries, and it is noted that the pardon was sealed personally in front of Edward III and Thomas, earl of Warwick.''\"\n\nRobert Herle was associated with the Bassett family of [[Drayton Bassett|Drayton]] in 1339 as retainer to the Bassett manors of [[Moulton, Northamptonshire|Moulton]], [[Long Buckby|Buckby]], [[Olney, Buckinghamshire|Olney]] and [[Walsall]].\n\n==Constable of Dover Castle and Lord Warden of the Cinque Ports==\n\nUntil now all lists state that the Lord Warden of the [[Cinque Ports]] for the year 1361 was Sir Richard de Herle, this was however not the case and in fact the appointment was granted to Sir Robert Herle. No evidence has been found in this short study for the existence of a Richard, and I conclude this to be an age old error now rectified.\n\n\"''By November of 1360 he is described as the \u2018king's lieutenant in [[Duchy of Brittany|Brittany]]\u2019, whilst a year later he was referred to as the \u2018king's admiral\u2019, and was Constable of [[Dover Castle]] and Lord Warden of the Cinque ports.''\" (see ref. below).\n\nIn addition from November 1354, Robert Herle acted for the king as the steward of the lands and castles of the king's sons, Edmund and John.\n\nIn addition to his long service to the earl of Warwick, during the later years of the 1340s Herle also became an important agent of the Crown and an officer of the king's household. He continued his service for, and close association with the earl of Warwick, who was instrumental in Herle's career, and is found named on a number of Warwick's most important charters between 1350-60.\n\n==Senior naval command==\nHe was appointed Commander-in-Chief of the English Navy from 2 December 1360 - 7 July 1364 with the title of [[Admiral of the Kings Southern, Northern and Western Fleets]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Rodger |first1=N.A.M. |title=The safeguard of the sea : a naval history of Britain. 660 to 1649 |date=2004 |publisher=W.W. Norton |location=New York |isbn=9780140297249 |pages=504\u2013506}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n===Footnotes===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Sources===\n* Nicolas, Sir Nicholas Harris (1847). A History of the Royal Navy: 1327-1422. London, England: R. Bentley.\n* Rodger, N.A.M. (2004). The safeguard of the sea : a naval history of Britain 660 to 1649. New York: W.W. Norton. {{ISBN|9780140297249}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110519040558/http://users.powernet.co.uk/barfield/chap3.htm Barfield and the Beauchamp family].\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box |\n  before=[[John Beauchamp, 3rd Baron Beauchamp de Somerset|The Lord Beauchamp de Somerset]] |\n  title=[[Lord Warden of the Cinque Ports]] |\n  years=1361&ndash;1364 |\n  after=The Lord Spigurnell\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n[[Category:English admirals]]\n[[Category:Lords Warden of the Cinque Ports|Herle, Robert de]]\n[[Category:14th-century English Navy personnel]]\n[[Category:1316 births]]\n[[Category:1364 deaths]]\n", "name_user": "J947", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: 1350-60 \u2192 1350\u201360 (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robert_de_Herle"}
{"title_page": "Matthew Croucher", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox military person\n|name= Matthew Croucher\n|image= \n|image_size= \n|alt= \n|caption= \n|nickname= \n|birth_date= {{birth date and age|1983|12|14|df=yes}}\n|birth_place= [[Solihull]], England\n|death_date= \n|death_place= \n|placeofburial= \n|allegiance= United Kingdom\n|branch= [[Royal Marines]]\n|serviceyears= 2000\u2013present\n|rank= [[Lance Corporal]]\n|servicenumber= \n|unit= [[40 Commando]]\n|commands= \n|battles= [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|War in Afghanistan]]<br/>[[Iraq War]]\n|awards= [[George Cross]]<br/>[[Volunteer Reserves Service Medal]]\n|relations= \n|laterwork= \n}}\n'''Matthew Croucher''', {{Post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|sep=,|GC|VR}} (born in 1983) is a member of the [[Royal Marines Reserve]] and a recipient of the [[George Cross]], the highest British and [[Commonwealth of Nations|Commonwealth]] medal for gallantry not in the face of the enemy, for his extreme valour in risking his life to safeguard the lives of his comrades. The award was announced by the [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]] on 23 July 2008,<ref name=MOD>{{Cite web|title=Royal Marine Reservist to receive the George Cross|url=http://www.mod.uk/DefenceInternet/DefenceNews/HistoryAndHonour/RoyalMarineReservistToReceiveTheGeorgeCross.htm|publisher=[[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]]| date = 23 July 2008 }}</ref> and [[London Gazette|gazetted]] on 24 July 2008, with a lengthy citation.<ref name=gazette>{{London Gazette|issue=58774|supp=y|pages=11163\u201311164|date=24 July 2008}}</ref><!-- the citation is [[Crown Copyright]], so we can't reproduce it in full -->\n\n==Early life==\nCroucher was born in [[Solihull]] in the [[West Midlands (county)|West Midlands]] in 1983<ref name=GCDB /> and attended [[Lyndon School, Solihull|Lyndon School]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://icsolihull.icnetwork.co.uk/news/local/tm_headline=i-thought-it-might-give-others-a-chance&method=full&objectid=21405904&siteid=91411-name_page.html|title=I thought it might give others a chance|work=icSolihull, [[Solihull Times]]|publisher=[[Trinity Mirror]]|date=25 July 2008|accessdate=25 July 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Military career==\nPrior to joining the [[Royal Marines]] in November 2000,<ref name=MOD /> he was a member of 2030 (Elmdon & Yardley) Squadron [[Air Training Corps]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.aircadets-wbw.org/news_matthew_croucher_gc.htm|title=Former Warwickshire and Birmingham Wing Air Cadet Awarded the George Cross|work=Warwickshire and Birmingham Wing ATC website|date=24 July 2008|accessdate=25 July 2008}}</ref> He served three tours in [[Iraq]] and one tour in [[Afghanistan]]. He was a member of [[40 Commando]] from 2002 to 2005 and again from 2007 to 2008. The unit is based at [[Taunton]] in [[Somerset]], and served in the Commando Reconnaissance Force.<ref name=gazette /> Before his Reserve Service, he was a member of the regular Corps of the Royal Marines. \n\nOn 9 November 2007 Croucher was credited with helping to save the life of a seriously wounded comrade who had been shot in the chest. Due to the intensity of the [[Battle|firefight]], the company medical assistant was [[pinned down]] and could not help for over 20 minutes, during which time Croucher stabilised the casualty until he could be evacuated.  Croucher himself was injured in a road accident during an operation the following week, and had to be returned to the United Kingdom for treatment on a suspected broken leg. After intensive physical therapy, he returned to Afghanistan in a matter of weeks to resume his duties.<ref name=gazette />\n\n===George Cross===\n[[File:Croucher, Matt (GC) backpack.JPG|thumb|right|The damaged backpack worn by Croucher along with some of his medals]]\nCroucher was recommended for the award for [[Falling on a grenade|throwing himself]] on a Taliban [[tripwire]] [[hand grenade|grenade]] to save his comrades. He was part of a reconnaissance mission near [[Sangin]] in [[Helmand Province]] in [[Afghanistan]] on 9 February 2008. Moving through a compound at night he felt a trip-wire against his leg and saw that he had activated a grenade. He threw himself to the ground, and used his [[Backpack|rucksack]] to pin the grenade to the floor, and tucked his legs up to his body.  He was thrown some distance by the explosion, but due to the protection offered by his rucksack and body-armour, suffered only a nose-bleed, perforated ear drums and some disorientation.  The pack was ripped from his back by the explosion, and his body armour and helmet were pitted by grenade fragments. Of the other three members of his patrol, the rear man managed to take cover by retreating round the corner of a building; the patrol commander threw himself to ground, and received a superficial face wound from a grenade fragment; and the final team member did not have time to react, and remained on his feet, and would have been within the lethal range of the grenade but for Croucher's action.  The explosion breached a large [[lithium battery]] which was in Croucher's pack to power the patrol's [[electronic countermeasures]] equipment, causing it to burst into flames.  A medic recommended that he be evacuated, but he insisted on continuing as the members of the patrol realised that Taliban fighters would probably come to investigate the explosion, and this would give the marines the opportunity to ambush them; the ambush was successful, and Croucher himself killed a Taliban fighter.<ref name=gazette /><ref>{{Cite news| title = Marine who threw himself on exploding grenade to protect comrades awarded George Cross|work=Daily Mail |location=UK| date = 23 July 2008| url = http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1037353/Marine-threw-exploding-grenade-protect-comrades-awarded-George-Cross.html| accessdate =23 July 2008}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news| last = Grey| first = Stephen| title = Lance Corporal Matt Croucher hurls himself onto Taliban grenade|work=The Sunday Times |location=UK| publisher=[[Times Newspapers Ltd]]| date = 30 March 2008| url = http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/asia/article3646243.ece| accessdate =31 March 2008}}</ref>\n\nCroucher was initially put forward for the [[Victoria Cross]] (VC), the highest decoration for valour in the [[British Armed Forces]]. Had he been awarded the Victoria Cross he would have been the first [[Royal Marine]] to receive the award since 1945 and only the second living British recipient in the 21st century. The [[George Cross]] (GC) is awarded for the same level of bravery expected of a VC but is awarded when no enemy is present. Croucher is one of only 22 [[List of living George Cross recipients|living recipients of the medal]], of which only 406 have been awarded.<ref name=GCDB>{{Cite web|work=The George Cross Database |url=http://www.gc-database.co.uk/living.htm |title=George Cross Living Recipients |accessdate=23 July 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080522181400/http://www.gc-database.co.uk/living.htm |archivedate=22 May 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=GCDBStats>{{Cite web|work=The George Cross Database |url=http://www.gc-database.co.uk/facts.htm |title=George Cross: Facts & Statistics, Matters of Interest and some Questions and Answers |accessdate=23 July 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080430163126/http://www.gc-database.co.uk/facts.htm |archivedate=30 April 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news| last = Harding| first = Thomas| title = Royal Marine who jumped on grenade awarded George Cross|work=The Daily Telegraph |location=UK| publisher=Telegraph Media Group Limited| date = 23 July 2008| url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/2445513/Royal-Marine-who-jumped-on-grenade-awarded-George-Cross.html}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news| last = Hickley| first = Matthew| title = Victoria Cross hope for Marine who leaped on a grenade to save friends|work=Daily Mail |location=UK| publisher=[[Associated Newspapers Ltd]]| date = 31 March 2008| url = http://www.dailymail.co.uk/pages/live/articles/news/worldnews.html?in_article_id=550689&in_page_id=1811| accessdate =31 March 2008}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news| last = Harding| first = Thomas| title = Heroic marine throws himself on grenade|work=The Daily Telegraph |location=UK| publisher=Telegraph Media Group Limited| date = 31 March 2008| url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/main.jhtml?xml=/news/2008/03/30/nhero130.xml| accessdate =31 March 2008}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news| title = Marine threw himself onto grenade|publisher=BBC News| date = 30 March 2008| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/west_midlands/7321647.stm| accessdate =31 March 2008}}</ref><!-- nb, awards have since been made to [[Olaf Schmid]] (posthumously) and [[Kim Hughes (GC)]], which these sources do not yet reflect, and where news items, will not be updated-->\n\nCroucher was presented with the GC by [[Elizabeth II|Queen Elizabeth II]] at a ceremony in [[Buckingham Palace]] on 30 October 2008.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2008/oct/31/7|title=News in brief\u2014George Cross for marine who saved comrades|author=[[Press Association]]|page=10|date=31 October 2008|accessdate=2 November 2008|location=London|work=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n<center>\n<br>\n[[File:UK George Cross ribbon.svg|100px]]\n[[File:Iraq medal ribbon bar with rosette.png|100px]]\n<br>\n[[File:OSM for Afghanistan w bar.svg|100px]]\n[[File:Queen Elizabeth II Golden Jubilee Medal ribbon.png|100px]]\n[[File:QEII Diamond Jubilee Medal ribbon.png|100px]]\n[[File:Volunteer Reserves Service Medal.png|100px]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:silver;\" align=\"center\"\n|Ribbon || Description || Notes\n|-\n|[[File:UK George Cross ribbon.svg|40px]] || [[George Cross]] (GC) || \n* 2008\n|-\n|[[File:Iraq medal ribbon bar with rosette.png|40px]] || [[Iraq Medal (United Kingdom)|Iraq Medal]] ||\n* With clasp \"19 Mar to 28 Apr 2003\"\n|-\n|[[File:OSM for Afghanistan w bar.svg|40px]] || [[Operational Service Medal for Afghanistan]] ||\n* With clasp \"AFGHANISTAN\"\n|-\n|[[File:Queen Elizabeth II Golden Jubilee Medal ribbon.png|40px]] || [[Queen Elizabeth II Golden Jubilee Medal]] ||\n* 2002\n* UK version of this medal\n|-\n|[[File:QEII Diamond Jubilee Medal ribbon.png|40px]] || [[Queen Elizabeth II Diamond Jubilee Medal]] ||\n* 2012\n* UK version of this medal\n|-\n|[[File:Volunteer Reserves Service Medal.png|40px]] || [[Volunteer Reserves Service Medal]]\n||\n* 10 years service in the [[Royal Marines Reserve]]. \n|-\n|}\n</center>\n\n* On 16 December 2008 he received the [[Freedom of the City|Freedom of the Borough]] of [[Solihull]].<ref>http://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/local-news/hero-soldier-matt-croucher-given-74871</ref><ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RtkvzA82KjI</ref>\n\n==Civilian career==\nCroucher is employed in the [[Private security company|private security industry]] by the United Kingdom offices of Pinnacle Risk Management as Managing & Operations Director. He also works out of the offices in [[Dubai]], [[United Arab Emirates]].<ref>https://www.linkedin.com/in/matt-croucher-gc-0244674a</ref>\n\n==Works==\n* ''Bulletproof'', [[Century (imprint)|Century]], 24 September 2009, {{ISBN|978-1-84605-704-5}}.\n* ''Flash Point'', [[Arrow Books]], 2010, {{ISBN|978-0-09-954313-8}}\n* ''90 Years of Heroes, Royal British Legion 90th Anniversary tribute,'' HarperCollins, 2011\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Croucher, Matthew}}\n[[Category:British recipients of the George Cross]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy personnel of the War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)]]\n[[Category:People from Solihull]]\n[[Category:Royal Marines ranks]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy personnel of the Iraq War]]\n[[Category:1983 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English autobiographers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox military person\n|name= Matthew Croucher\n|image= \n|image_size= \n|alt= \n|caption= \n|nickname= \n|birth_date= {{birth date and age|1983|12|14}}\n|birth_place= [[Solihull]], England\n|death_date= \n|death_place= \n|placeofburial= \n|allegiance= United Kingdom\n|branch= [[Royal Marines]]\n|serviceyears= 2000\u2013present\n|rank= [[Lance Corporal]]\n|servicenumber= \n|unit= [[40 Commando]]\n|commands= \n|battles= [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|War in Afghanistan]]<br/>[[Iraq War]]\n|awards= [[George Cross]]<br/>[[Volunteer Reserves Service Medal]]\n|relations= \n|laterwork= \n}}\n'''Matthew Croucher''', {{Post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|sep=,|GC|VR}} (born in 1983) is a member of the [[Royal Marines Reserve]] and a recipient of the [[George Cross]], the highest British and [[Commonwealth of Nations|Commonwealth]] medal for gallantry not in the face of the enemy, for his extreme valour in risking his life to safeguard the lives of his comrades. The award was announced by the [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]] on 23 July 2008,<ref name=MOD>{{Cite web|title=Royal Marine Reservist to receive the George Cross|url=http://www.mod.uk/DefenceInternet/DefenceNews/HistoryAndHonour/RoyalMarineReservistToReceiveTheGeorgeCross.htm|publisher=[[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]]| date = 23 July 2008 }}</ref> and [[London Gazette|gazetted]] on 24 July 2008, with a lengthy citation.<ref name=gazette>{{London Gazette|issue=58774|supp=y|pages=11163\u201311164|date=24 July 2008}}</ref><!-- the citation is [[Crown Copyright]], so we can't reproduce it in full -->\n\n==Early life==\nCroucher was born in [[Solihull]] in the [[West Midlands (county)|West Midlands]] in 1983<ref name=GCDB /> and attended [[Lyndon School, Solihull|Lyndon School]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://icsolihull.icnetwork.co.uk/news/local/tm_headline=i-thought-it-might-give-others-a-chance&method=full&objectid=21405904&siteid=91411-name_page.html|title=I thought it might give others a chance|work=icSolihull, [[Solihull Times]]|publisher=[[Trinity Mirror]]|date=25 July 2008|accessdate=25 July 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Military career==\nPrior to joining the [[Royal Marines]] in November 2000,<ref name=MOD /> he was a member of 2030 (Elmdon & Yardley) Squadron [[Air Training Corps]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.aircadets-wbw.org/news_matthew_croucher_gc.htm|title=Former Warwickshire and Birmingham Wing Air Cadet Awarded the George Cross|work=Warwickshire and Birmingham Wing ATC website|date=24 July 2008|accessdate=25 July 2008}}</ref> He served three tours in [[Iraq]] and one tour in [[Afghanistan]]. He was a member of [[40 Commando]] from 2002 to 2005 and again from 2007 to 2008. The unit is based at [[Taunton]] in [[Somerset]], and served in the Commando Reconnaissance Force.<ref name=gazette /> Before his Reserve Service, he was a member of the regular Corps of the Royal Marines. \n\nOn 9 November 2007 Croucher was credited with helping to save the life of a seriously wounded comrade who had been shot in the chest. Due to the intensity of the [[Battle|firefight]], the company medical assistant was [[pinned down]] and could not help for over 20 minutes, during which time Croucher stabilised the casualty until he could be evacuated.  Croucher himself was injured in a road accident during an operation the following week, and had to be returned to the United Kingdom for treatment on a suspected broken leg. After intensive physical therapy, he returned to Afghanistan in a matter of weeks to resume his duties.<ref name=gazette />\n\n===George Cross===\n[[File:Croucher, Matt (GC) backpack.JPG|thumb|right|The damaged backpack worn by Croucher along with some of his medals]]\nCroucher was recommended for the award for [[Falling on a grenade|throwing himself]] on a Taliban [[tripwire]] [[hand grenade|grenade]] to save his comrades. He was part of a reconnaissance mission near [[Sangin]] in [[Helmand Province]] in [[Afghanistan]] on 9 February 2008. Moving through a compound at night he felt a trip-wire against his leg and saw that he had activated a grenade. He threw himself to the ground, and used his [[Backpack|rucksack]] to pin the grenade to the floor, and tucked his legs up to his body.  He was thrown some distance by the explosion, but due to the protection offered by his rucksack and body-armour, suffered only a nose-bleed, perforated ear drums and some disorientation.  The pack was ripped from his back by the explosion, and his body armour and helmet were pitted by grenade fragments. Of the other three members of his patrol, the rear man managed to take cover by retreating round the corner of a building; the patrol commander threw himself to ground, and received a superficial face wound from a grenade fragment; and the final team member did not have time to react, and remained on his feet, and would have been within the lethal range of the grenade but for Croucher's action.  The explosion breached a large [[lithium battery]] which was in Croucher's pack to power the patrol's [[electronic countermeasures]] equipment, causing it to burst into flames.  A medic recommended that he be evacuated, but he insisted on continuing as the members of the patrol realised that Taliban fighters would probably come to investigate the explosion, and this would give the marines the opportunity to ambush them; the ambush was successful, and Croucher himself killed a Taliban fighter.<ref name=gazette /><ref>{{Cite news| title = Marine who threw himself on exploding grenade to protect comrades awarded George Cross|work=Daily Mail |location=UK| date = 23 July 2008| url = http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1037353/Marine-threw-exploding-grenade-protect-comrades-awarded-George-Cross.html| accessdate =23 July 2008}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news| last = Grey| first = Stephen| title = Lance Corporal Matt Croucher hurls himself onto Taliban grenade|work=The Sunday Times |location=UK| publisher=[[Times Newspapers Ltd]]| date = 30 March 2008| url = http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/asia/article3646243.ece| accessdate =31 March 2008}}</ref>\n\nCroucher was initially put forward for the [[Victoria Cross]] (VC), the highest decoration for valour in the [[British Armed Forces]]. Had he been awarded the Victoria Cross he would have been the first [[Royal Marine]] to receive the award since 1945 and only the second living British recipient in the 21st century. The [[George Cross]] (GC) is awarded for the same level of bravery expected of a VC but is awarded when no enemy is present. Croucher is one of only 22 [[List of living George Cross recipients|living recipients of the medal]], of which only 406 have been awarded.<ref name=GCDB>{{Cite web|work=The George Cross Database |url=http://www.gc-database.co.uk/living.htm |title=George Cross Living Recipients |accessdate=23 July 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080522181400/http://www.gc-database.co.uk/living.htm |archivedate=22 May 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=GCDBStats>{{Cite web|work=The George Cross Database |url=http://www.gc-database.co.uk/facts.htm |title=George Cross: Facts & Statistics, Matters of Interest and some Questions and Answers |accessdate=23 July 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080430163126/http://www.gc-database.co.uk/facts.htm |archivedate=30 April 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news| last = Harding| first = Thomas| title = Royal Marine who jumped on grenade awarded George Cross|work=The Daily Telegraph |location=UK| publisher=Telegraph Media Group Limited| date = 23 July 2008| url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/2445513/Royal-Marine-who-jumped-on-grenade-awarded-George-Cross.html}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news| last = Hickley| first = Matthew| title = Victoria Cross hope for Marine who leaped on a grenade to save friends|work=Daily Mail |location=UK| publisher=[[Associated Newspapers Ltd]]| date = 31 March 2008| url = http://www.dailymail.co.uk/pages/live/articles/news/worldnews.html?in_article_id=550689&in_page_id=1811| accessdate =31 March 2008}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news| last = Harding| first = Thomas| title = Heroic marine throws himself on grenade|work=The Daily Telegraph |location=UK| publisher=Telegraph Media Group Limited| date = 31 March 2008| url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/main.jhtml?xml=/news/2008/03/30/nhero130.xml| accessdate =31 March 2008}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news| title = Marine threw himself onto grenade|publisher=BBC News| date = 30 March 2008| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/west_midlands/7321647.stm| accessdate =31 March 2008}}</ref><!-- nb, awards have since been made to [[Olaf Schmid]] (posthumously) and [[Kim Hughes (GC)]], which these sources do not yet reflect, and where news items, will not be updated-->\n\nCroucher was presented with the GC by [[Elizabeth II|Queen Elizabeth II]] at a ceremony in [[Buckingham Palace]] on 30 October 2008.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2008/oct/31/7|title=News in brief\u2014George Cross for marine who saved comrades|author=[[Press Association]]|page=10|date=31 October 2008|accessdate=2 November 2008|location=London|work=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n<center>\n<br>\n[[File:UK George Cross ribbon.svg|100px]]\n[[File:Iraq medal ribbon bar with rosette.png|100px]]\n<br>\n[[File:OSM for Afghanistan w bar.svg|100px]]\n[[File:Queen Elizabeth II Golden Jubilee Medal ribbon.png|100px]]\n[[File:QEII Diamond Jubilee Medal ribbon.png|100px]]\n[[File:Volunteer Reserves Service Medal.png|100px]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:silver;\" align=\"center\"\n|Ribbon || Description || Notes\n|-\n|[[File:UK George Cross ribbon.svg|40px]] || [[George Cross]] (GC) || \n* 2008\n|-\n|[[File:Iraq medal ribbon bar with rosette.png|40px]] || [[Iraq Medal (United Kingdom)|Iraq Medal]] ||\n* With clasp \"19 Mar to 28 Apr 2003\"\n|-\n|[[File:OSM for Afghanistan w bar.svg|40px]] || [[Operational Service Medal for Afghanistan]] ||\n* With clasp \"AFGHANISTAN\"\n|-\n|[[File:Queen Elizabeth II Golden Jubilee Medal ribbon.png|40px]] || [[Queen Elizabeth II Golden Jubilee Medal]] ||\n* 2002\n* UK version of this medal\n|-\n|[[File:QEII Diamond Jubilee Medal ribbon.png|40px]] || [[Queen Elizabeth II Diamond Jubilee Medal]] ||\n* 2012\n* UK version of this medal\n|-\n|[[File:Volunteer Reserves Service Medal.png|40px]] || [[Volunteer Reserves Service Medal]]\n||\n* 10 years service in the [[Royal Marines Reserve]]. \n|-\n|}\n</center>\n\n* On 16 December 2008 he received the [[Freedom of the City|Freedom of the Borough]] of [[Solihull]].<ref>http://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/local-news/hero-soldier-matt-croucher-given-74871</ref><ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RtkvzA82KjI</ref>\n\n==Civilian career==\nCroucher is employed in the [[Private security company|private security industry]] by the United Kingdom offices of Pinnacle Risk Management as Managing & Operations Director. He also works out of the offices in [[Dubai]], [[United Arab Emirates]].<ref>https://www.linkedin.com/in/matt-croucher-gc-0244674a</ref>\n\n==Works==\n* ''Bulletproof'', [[Century (imprint)|Century]], 24 September 2009, {{ISBN|978-1-84605-704-5}}.\n* ''Flash Point'', [[Arrow Books]], 2010, {{ISBN|978-0-09-954313-8}}\n* ''90 Years of Heroes, Royal British Legion 90th Anniversary tribute,'' HarperCollins, 2011\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Croucher, Matthew}}\n[[Category:British recipients of the George Cross]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy personnel of the War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)]]\n[[Category:People from Solihull]]\n[[Category:Royal Marines ranks]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy personnel of the Iraq War]]\n[[Category:1983 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English autobiographers]]\n", "name_user": "Abraham, B.S.", "label": "safe", "comment": "df=yes", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matthew_Croucher"}
{"title_page": "Simon Vallily", "text_new": "{{Short description|English boxer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2015}}\n{{Infobox boxer\n| name = kokot slab\u00fd\n| image = \n| caption = \n| realname =\n| nickname = \n| weight = [[Heavyweight]]<br />[[Cruiserweight (boxing)|Cruiserweight]]\n| height = \n| reach = \n| nationality = British\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1985|8|15|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Middlesbrough]], [[Yorkshire]],<br/>England\n| style = [[Orthodox stance|Orthodox]]\n| total = 20\n| wins = 17\n| KO = 7\n| losses = 2\n| draws =  1\n| no contests = \n| medaltemplates = \n{{MedalSport | Men's [[amateur boxing]]}}\n{{MedalCountry | {{ENG}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Commonwealth Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold | [[2010 Commonwealth Games|2010 Delhi]] | [[Boxing at the 2010 Commonwealth Games \u2013 Heavyweight|Heavyweight]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Simon Vallily''' (born 15 August 1985) is an English [[professional boxer]]. As an amateur, he was a member of the England elite squad as well as the Great British podium squad and won gold at the [[2010 Commonwealth Games]] in [[Delhi]]. Vallily was born to English father and Jamaican mother.<ref name=\"www.gbboxing.org.uk/boxers/simon-vallily GB Boxing\">{{Cite web |url= http://www.gbboxing.org.uk/boxers/simon-vallily# |title=GB Boxing {{!}} Simon Vallily profile |access-date=14 November 2010 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100326021413/http://www.gbboxing.org.uk/boxers/simon-vallily# |archive-date=26 March 2010 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"www.guardian.co.uk/sport/2010/oct/13/simon-vallily-commonwealth-games The Guardian\">[https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2010/oct/13/simon-vallily-commonwealth-games The Guardian | Boxer Simon Vallily gets redemption with gold]</ref>\n\n==Amateur career==\nFighting for the South Bank Amateur boxing club in [[Middlesbrough]], Vallily was formerly on the books of [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough Football Club]] until disciplinary issues meant that his career in football ended prematurely.<ref name=\"www.gazettelive.co.uk\" /><ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/commonwealthgames/8062043/Commonwealth-Games-2010-Simon-Vallily-claims-heavyweight-gold-after-knockout.html The Telegraph | Simon Vallily claims heavyweight gold after kncokout]</ref>  Vallily claimed that he started boxing after getting into trouble when he was a kid, and that what he would be doing if he were not boxing would be \"not worth thinking about\".<ref name=\"www.gbboxing.org.uk/boxers/simon-vallily GB Boxing\" />  In February 2006, he was sentenced to 4 years in prison following a knife attack.  Halfway into his sentence he was released and started to concentrate on his boxing career.<ref name=\"www.gazettelive.co.uk\">[http://www.gazettelive.co.uk/north-east-sport/boxing-news/2010/10/26/simon-vallily-is-now-realising-his-potential-84229-27544249/ Gazette Live | Simon Vallily only now reaching his potential]</ref>\n\n===Domestic honours===\nIn 2009, competing in the super heavyweight division, Vallily won the senior ABA title in Sheffield at the English Institute of Sport, beating Amin Isa 13-4.  Despite touching the canvas himself, the victory included a knockdown of his opponent in the third round.  Speaking of the win and of the fact that he himself had taken a count, Vallily said, \"Getting caught gave me a kick up the backside and got me going\".  Reflecting on the turnaround in his life since being sentenced to jail in 2006 Vallily said, \"I've changed since those days and I'm an ABA champion now...All that is behind me and I don't like to look back - I was just a daft kid...I want to look to the future. I'm grown up now and more focused and this is just the start\".<ref>[http://www.gazettelive.co.uk/north-east-sport/boxing-news/2009/05/09/simon-vallily-wins-senior-aba-boxing-title-84229-23583386/ Gazette Live | Simon Vallily wins senior boxing title]</ref>  On 13 November 2010, Vallily was crowned the Great Britain champion after defeating experienced rival Danny Price 4-3 in the tournament held in Liverpool's Echo Arena and televised by the BBC.<ref>[http://www.sportinglife.com/boxing/news/story_get.cgi?STORY_NAME=boxing/10/11/13/BOXING_Amateur_2nd_Nightlead.html Sporting Life | Vallily crowned GB champion]{{dead link|date=May 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n===Commonwealth Games===\nVallily was part of the England team that competed at the [[2010 Commonwealth Games]] in Delhi.  Picked at the [[Boxing at the 2010 Commonwealth Games \u2013 Heavyweight|91kg Heavyweight]] category, Vallily fought his way to the final, defeating Dominic Winrow of the [[Isle of Man]] in the first round, Arsene Foukou of [[Cameroon]] in the quarter-finals and gaining a walkover against [[Awusone Yekeni]] of [[Ghana]] in the semifinals.<ref>[http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/sport/8449006.Saunders_and_Vallily_going_for_gold/ Northern Echo | Vallily and Saunders through to final]</ref>  In the final he claimed the gold medal with a first round stoppage over Northern Ireland's Steven Ward after knocking him to the canvas, having quickly established a 6-1 lead.  Speaking of Vallily's performance, coach [[Rob McCracken]] said \"He's frighteningly good. We've got two years to work with him and there's a real possibility he could win the Olympics\".<ref name=\"www.guardian.co.uk/sport/2010/oct/13/simon-vallily-commonwealth-games The Guardian\" />\n\n==Professional boxing record==\n{{BoxingRecordSummary\n|draws=1\n|nc=\n|ko-wins=4\n|ko-losses=2\n|dec-wins=9\n|dec-losses=\n|dq-wins=\n|dq-losses=\n}}\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:95%\"\n|-\n!{{abbr|No.|Number}}\n!Result\n!Record\n!Opponent\n!Type\n!Round, time\n!Date\n!Location\n!Notes\n|-\n|17\n|\n|14-2-1\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|UK}} Fabio Wardley\n|\n|\n|4 Apr 2020\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|UK}} {{small|Metro Radio Arena, Newcastle, England}