\u20130\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|UK}} Simeon Cover\n|PTS\n|4\n|21 Mar 2013\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|UK}} {{small|[[York Hall]], [[Bethnal Green]], [[London]], England}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{small|Professional debut}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{boxrec|id=640357}}\n\n{{Footer Commonwealth Champions Heavyweight}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vallily, Simon}}\n[[Category:1985 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English male boxers]]\n[[Category:Cruiserweight boxers]]\n[[Category:Boxers at the 2010 Commonwealth Games]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games gold medallists for England]]\n[[Category:England Boxing champions]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Middlesbrough]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games medallists in boxing]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|English boxer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2015}}\n{{Infobox boxer\n| name = Simon Vallily\n| image = \n| caption = \n| realname =\n| nickname = \n| weight = [[Heavyweight]]<br />[[Cruiserweight (boxing)|Cruiserweight]]\n| height = \n| reach = \n| nationality = British\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1985|8|15|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Middlesbrough]], [[Yorkshire]],<br/>England\n| style = [[Orthodox stance|Orthodox]]\n| total = 20\n| wins = 17\n| KO = 7\n| losses = 2\n| draws =  1\n| no contests = \n| medaltemplates = \n{{MedalSport | Men's [[amateur boxing]]}}\n{{MedalCountry | {{ENG}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Commonwealth Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold | [[2010 Commonwealth Games|2010 Delhi]] | [[Boxing at the 2010 Commonwealth Games \u2013 Heavyweight|Heavyweight]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Simon Vallily''' (born 15 August 1985) is an English [[professional boxer]]. As an amateur, he was a member of the England elite squad as well as the Great British podium squad and won gold at the [[2010 Commonwealth Games]] in [[Delhi]]. Vallily was born to English father and Jamaican mother.<ref name=\"www.gbboxing.org.uk/boxers/simon-vallily GB Boxing\">{{Cite web |url= http://www.gbboxing.org.uk/boxers/simon-vallily# |title=GB Boxing {{!}} Simon Vallily profile |access-date=14 November 2010 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100326021413/http://www.gbboxing.org.uk/boxers/simon-vallily# |archive-date=26 March 2010 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"www.guardian.co.uk/sport/2010/oct/13/simon-vallily-commonwealth-games The Guardian\">[https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2010/oct/13/simon-vallily-commonwealth-games The Guardian | Boxer Simon Vallily gets redemption with gold]</ref>\n\n==Amateur career==\nFighting for the South Bank Amateur boxing club in [[Middlesbrough]], Vallily was formerly on the books of [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough Football Club]] until disciplinary issues meant that his career in football ended prematurely.<ref name=\"www.gazettelive.co.uk\" /><ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/commonwealthgames/8062043/Commonwealth-Games-2010-Simon-Vallily-claims-heavyweight-gold-after-knockout.html The Telegraph | Simon Vallily claims heavyweight gold after kncokout]</ref>  Vallily claimed that he started boxing after getting into trouble when he was a kid, and that what he would be doing if he were not boxing would be \"not worth thinking about\".<ref name=\"www.gbboxing.org.uk/boxers/simon-vallily GB Boxing\" />  In February 2006, he was sentenced to 4 years in prison following a knife attack.  Halfway into his sentence he was released and started to concentrate on his boxing career.<ref name=\"www.gazettelive.co.uk\">[http://www.gazettelive.co.uk/north-east-sport/boxing-news/2010/10/26/simon-vallily-is-now-realising-his-potential-84229-27544249/ Gazette Live | Simon Vallily only now reaching his potential]</ref>\n\n===Domestic honours===\nIn 2009, competing in the super heavyweight division, Vallily won the senior ABA title in Sheffield at the English Institute of Sport, beating Amin Isa 13-4.  Despite touching the canvas himself, the victory included a knockdown of his opponent in the third round.  Speaking of the win and of the fact that he himself had taken a count, Vallily said, \"Getting caught gave me a kick up the backside and got me going\".  Reflecting on the turnaround in his life since being sentenced to jail in 2006 Vallily said, \"I've changed since those days and I'm an ABA champion now...All that is behind me and I don't like to look back - I was just a daft kid...I want to look to the future. I'm grown up now and more focused and this is just the start\".<ref>[http://www.gazettelive.co.uk/north-east-sport/boxing-news/2009/05/09/simon-vallily-wins-senior-aba-boxing-title-84229-23583386/ Gazette Live | Simon Vallily wins senior boxing title]</ref>  On 13 November 2010, Vallily was crowned the Great Britain champion after defeating experienced rival Danny Price 4-3 in the tournament held in Liverpool's Echo Arena and televised by the BBC.<ref>[http://www.sportinglife.com/boxing/news/story_get.cgi?STORY_NAME=boxing/10/11/13/BOXING_Amateur_2nd_Nightlead.html Sporting Life | Vallily crowned GB champion]{{dead link|date=May 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n===Commonwealth Games===\nVallily was part of the England team that competed at the [[2010 Commonwealth Games]] in Delhi.  Picked at the [[Boxing at the 2010 Commonwealth Games \u2013 Heavyweight|91kg Heavyweight]] category, Vallily fought his way to the final, defeating Dominic Winrow of the [[Isle of Man]] in the first round, Arsene Foukou of [[Cameroon]] in the quarter-finals and gaining a walkover against [[Awusone Yekeni]] of [[Ghana]] in the semifinals.<ref>[http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/sport/8449006.Saunders_and_Vallily_going_for_gold/ Northern Echo | Vallily and Saunders through to final]</ref>  In the final he claimed the gold medal with a first round stoppage over Northern Ireland's Steven Ward after knocking him to the canvas, having quickly established a 6-1 lead.  Speaking of Vallily's performance, coach [[Rob McCracken]] said \"He's frighteningly good. We've got two years to work with him and there's a real possibility he could win the Olympics\".<ref name=\"www.guardian.co.uk/sport/2010/oct/13/simon-vallily-commonwealth-games The Guardian\" />\n\n==Professional boxing record==\n{{BoxingRecordSummary\n|draws=1\n|nc=\n|ko-wins=4\n|ko-losses=2\n|dec-wins=9\n|dec-losses=\n|dq-wins=\n|dq-losses=\n}}\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:95%\"\n|-\n!{{abbr|No.|Number}}\n!Result\n!Record\n!Opponent\n!Type\n!Round, time\n!Date\n!Location\n!Notes\n|-\n|17\n|\n|14-2-1\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|UK}} Fabio Wardley\n|\n|\n|4 Apr 2020\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|UK}} {{small|Metro Radio Arena, Newcastle, England}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|\n|-\n|16\n|{{no2}}Loss\n|13\u20132\u20131\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|UK}} Craig Glover\n|TKO\n|8 (10), {{small|1:06}}\n|13 Oct 2018\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|UK}} {{small|Metro Radio Arena, Newcastle, England}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|\n|-\n|15\n|{{draw}}Draw\n|13\u20131\u20131\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|UK}} Arfan Iqbal\n|SD\n|10\n|16 Jun 2018\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|UK}} {{small|Metro Radio Arena, Newcastle, England}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{small|For English cruiserweight title}}\n|-\n|14\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|13\u20131\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|CMR}} Blaise Mendouo\n|TKO\n|4 (4), {{small|2:24}}\n|17 Feb 2018\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|UK}} {{small|[[Manchester Arena]], [[Manchester]], England}}\n|\n|-\n|13\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|12\u20131\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|CMR}} [[Blaise Yepmou|Blaise Mendouo]]\n|PTS\n|6\n|23 Jun 2017\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|UK}} {{small|Walker Activity Dome, [[Newcastle upon Tyne|Newcastle]], [[Tyne and Wear]], England}}\n|\n|-\n|12\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|11\u20131\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|LIT}} Dmitrij Kalinovskij\n|PTS\n|4\n|26 May 20